### String Interpolation

Before C# 6, formatting strings required clunky methods like `string.Format("Hello {0}", name)`.

Now, C# has **String Interpolation**. By placing a `$` symbol right before the opening quote of a string, you can inject variables directly into the string by wrapping them in curly braces `{ }`.

**Example:**
```csharp
int age = 30;
string name = "Bob";
string sentence = $"{name} is {age} years old.";
// Result: "Bob is 30 years old."
```

