### Try / Catch

When your code does something dangerous (like dividing by zero, or parsing a bad string), C# throws an **Exception**. If you don't catch it, your app crashes!

We use a `try / catch` block to handle these gracefully.

**Example:**
```csharp
try 
{
    int result = int.Parse("Not a number");
}
catch (FormatException ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine("That wasn't a valid number!");
}
```

