### The Dependency Inversion Principle

The **D** in SOLID says: *"Depend on abstractions, not on concretions."*

Instead of hard-coding a dependency on a specific class, accept an **interface** through the constructor:

```csharp
public interface ILogger
{
    void Log(string message);
}
public class App
{
    private readonly ILogger _logger;
    public App(ILogger logger) { _logger = logger; }
    public void Run() { _logger.Log("Started"); }
}
```

Now you can swap `ConsoleLogger`, `FileLogger`, or a mock for testing — without changing `App`.

